info.remarks:
Circumstances
Found Sat. 19 Oct. 1991 by Mr. Lawley on the beach below Birling Gap. There had been a storm the previous day and the sea was now unusually low. He found the axe wedged between stones (not large boulders) at a point roughly 50 m west of the base of the steps, and 20-25 m from the then sea-line. A second object, seemingly of cast iron and 'knuckle duster' like was on the pebbles nearby.

info.remarks: One of nine implements found at "Seaward" by workmen. This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum; extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most un-cooperative. The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.
info.description: Discovered by workmen digging a drainage inspection box immediately to the south of the front door of "Seaward", The Ridings, East Preston (TQ 068018). Found 18 inches deep in clay mould. Found July, 1954.[;]Late Bronze Age palstave with stop-ridge and loop. Two raised ribs below and almost at right angles to stop-ridge. Both flanges on one side damaged.

info.description: Dimensions: L 169mm; We 70.5mm; Bfg. 26.6mm; min B st. 21.3mm; max T sep 8.4mm[;]Typology: septum floor slightly dished, with quite angular corners and tendency for pointed end especially on reverse; bt. end slightly thick - but rounded, not neat; flattened stop crests and parts of fgs; shield-shaped depression - no encircling rib, vertical ridge-and-furrows inside - 4 or 5, some vague[;]Manufacture: alight traces only of cg. fl - well removed; edge bev. - line diffuse due to corrosion? very slight blade tip hollows; srmks and pmks on sides - diagonal and longitudinal - anc. mainly; pore hole low in one fg.; odd longit pmks in septum[;]Condition: edge blunt but intact - partly anc. blunting partly corrosion damage; odd gold flecks on corners, etc. - mod. interference; little corrosion damage at butt perhaps[;]Attached Material: patches of fawn soil adhering

info.description: Dimensions: L 164.3mm; We 38.2mm; Wbt 22.3mm; Bst. 37mm; Blp 9.3mm; T sep 16.6mm; Tbt 7.5mm[;]Typology: five short ribs on either face, outer ones slightly thinner - terminals emphasised by  forged bev.; angular blade edges; rounded st. and fg. crests - latter very narrow; slight bowing to butt faces[;]Manufacture: some fg. ends clipped by hammering; cg. fl. remains only on flange sides only - totally removed from butt and blade sides - some hammer marks here; part of cg. fl. quite sharp - untrimmed; small irregular bulbous mouldings on fg. and sl - defects; slight hammermark damage much of blade, with qt. distinct; edge bev. low down; cavities in one septum end - cg. flaws[;]Condition: butt top - broken surface - probably in manufacturing; edge basically in tact, blunted from patina flaking; crests on one face - corrosion chipped.[;]Attached Material: Chalky to fawn  matrix mainly in hollows

info.description: Dimensions: L 132.2mm; EWe 46.0mm; Wbt 24.5mm; Bst 34.0mm; Blp 8.6mm; T sep 15.2mm; Tbb 5.7 mm (approx)[;]Typology: five irregularly spaced ribs - 2 outer ones very thing - flatten at bases and merge out; angular square-ended septum; blade cast with a flare below decoration; rounded fg. crests - medium broad; inner edge of stop qt. angular bevelled underside; bev. on septum across fg. ends[;]Manufacture: blade faces cast or forged into 4 longitudinal facets - few individual hammer marks possibly discernible; broad stumps of cg. fl. - some practically or totally removed - hammer marks; hammer flattening of fg. ends; 2 valves of mould dislocated; loop asymmetric., septums different lengths;  asymmetric fg. section; small proj. on one side - cg. defect?; much of butt-end smoothed.[;]Condition: virtually all of edge lost - chipped to pale green and dark chocolate brown; fgs and sts mainly undamaged[;]Attached Material: light orangey-brown soil traces in many places

info.description: Dimensions: L 151.3mm; Wbl.e 35.6mm; Wbt 19.5mm; max B bt 5.5mm; T sep 14.5mm; B st. 31.7mm; Blp 10.2mm[;]Typology: crisp body angles to butt end, but each with facet, just below end; fg. crests mainly rounded to flat and undulating; underside of st. bevelled - reverse one more regular; constriction at top of blade not defined by neat side bevels; blade angles crisp; septum angles fairly crisp, corners little rounded, end little bowed; both septums offset to right at bottom[;]Manufacture: low fairly narrow stump of cg. fl. on loop - rounded with some battering; above loop and on central part of reverse side low broad flat-topped cg. fl with hammer marks, but no  sign lpg.; fully removed elsewhere on sides, where some suggestion of hammer marks, also on lower blade; very slight hollows immediately beneath stops on faces - probably cg. flaws; some irregularity on fg. insides - as cast[;]Condition: butt end a broken surface - untampered with; blade edge more or less intact, but not sharp, possibly due to det.; band of diagonal grmks. up on blade face - pres. modern but no diff. colour[;]Attached Material: butt soil traces, especially on butt end and under lp.

This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum: extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence';'given to my child for his school museum'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most unco- operative. info.description: Typology: sl. irreg. bev. across fg. tops on sep. ; one sep. little wider than other - both curved bottoms in cross-sec. with rounded angles ; fg. and stop crests neat rounded - no distict bevels ; stops little depress in centre ; short fg. extensions onto bd. with flattened crests tending to splay at bases; midrib low rounded [...] [?bumps] without crisp bevels - one extends virt. to e. bev, other higher, but as short as fg. extensions ; sides sl. bowed in cross-sec. ; e.g. fl. remains as v. broad low rounded bump - less pronounced on either side, virt. all trace removed on bl. sides, with some hammer rippling; dimples generally even sur. - hmks or moulding?  Swallow hole in end of one sep.,depression in other; e. bevs. little diffuse - assoc. hmks most of bl. e. irreg. - prob. from chipping of p., but one large chip def. anc. with p. intact; p. frag. also in one butt depression - irreg. line prob. orig. ; 2 or 3 small gougings of p., prob. recent, including one blade angle forming facet ; short intact stretches of bl. e. suggest one fairly sharp

info.description:
L 154.4mm; We 59.3; Wst 32.3; Wbb 23.0; Bfg 26.0; Bst. 27.5; Wt 440.2 
Typology: Fg insides well sloped to rounded angles with sl. curved sep. floor; sep end sub rect; shield rib begins at lower level than fg/stop, and divided on either face by central rib; bl sec near rect - only sl. bowed faces; one sep rather longer than the other. 
Manufacture: some dimpling/undulations in p. extant prob from moulding; cg flash survives only as sl. step, or differential sur. condition; diffuse e.ber prob. originally sharp and quite steep;
Condition: bl. e. a little jagged - quite likely intact before corrosion; fissures across based of 3 fgs. just above stop- poss dam.; butt close to orig shape, but notch uncertain.
Surface: olive green p. preserved in small patches on sides and blade, and over most of the septums; mainly flaked to fir green dry sur. with lighter green pockings; small areas on bl. stripped down to gold metal. 
Conserved at London Institute of Archaeology lab - lab no 3889.
Chalky fawn soil desposit engrained in p. in sep ends. 
Context single find

info.description: Typology: shield depression on blade with no encircling rib; stop thick with round bevel - slightly dipped towards either flange; sl. bar ridges on sides; cross-section - sep. floor curved, inside angles sl. rounded, fg crests rounded; v. diffuse bev. across fg. tops on butt;[;]Manufacture: butt end a broken sur. from snapping off cg.jet; shallow hole in one sep. end, one half partly filled with more vesicular metal; cg. flash well removed for most part - evident as groove and or ridge; neat high e. bev. plus two (or one on sev.) close to edge; v. sl. blade tip hollows; dimpling in p. on sides and in septums - prob. in the moulding; hammering of tops of two flanges has caused sl. lipping on one side.[;]Condition: some minor denting of edge, stretches fairly sharp; tips both a little blunted - one retains patina, the other & all of rev. bl. face polished to bright gold colour by finder;  crack across the base of one fg. - dam? - another sur. fissure across one corner of blade;
